Cyclistic Case Study

  • Show All Code
  • Hide All Code
  • View Source
Author

Dóra Szefcsik

Background

Industry

According to the Meddin bike-sharing map, bike-sharing systems are present in 1,590 cities, in 92 countries and on every continent (except Antarctica). In April 2023, the world had 1,914 systems in operation with a fleet of 8,980,314 bikes. For the latest industry trends, read The Meddin Bike-sharing World Map Report. The origins of bike-sharing can be traced back to grassroots efforts in the Netherlands in the mid-1960s. For more historical context, see Bloomberg.

Company

Cyclistic is a (fictional) bike-share company launched in 2016. It operates a fleet of 5,824 bikes that are geotracked and locked into a network of 1419 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system at any time.

Business Task

Until now, Cyclistic’s marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped achieve this was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships.

Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders and customers who buy annual memberships are called Cyclistic members. In order to maximize revenue for the bike-sharing company, management set a clear objective to develop marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members.

The focus of the analysis

Analysing historical bike trip data to identify trends that can guide Cyclistic’s future marketing program.

Business Questions

In what ways do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

  • What time of the day/week/month/year do members and casual riders use the service?

  • Do members and casual users differ in the time they spend cycling?

  • What types of bikes do members and casual users prefer?

  • Are there any other differences that can help us better understand the needs of occasional and year-round users?

Preparing the data

Data Sources

The dataset is acquired from Divvy’s public data and made available by Motivate International Inc. under this license. It includes bike rides between 1 April 2022 and 31 March 2023.

Data Credibility

  • Reliable: Lyft Bikes and Scooters, LLC (Bikeshare) operates the City of Chicago’s Divvy bicycle sharing service. Bikeshare makes certain Divvy system data owned by the City available to the public. The City of Chicago owns all right, title, and interest in the Data.

  • Original: the data is collected by the Divvy systems

  • Comprehensive: the data contains all critical information needed to answer the business question

  • Current: the data covers the last 12 month

  • Cited: the data is collected and maintained by a credible organization

  • Complies with Data Privacy: the data is anonymised and does not contain any personally identifiable information

  • Unbiased: contains data that is representative of all users of the bike share service

Downloading and storing the data

  1. Downloaded the data that covers the last 12 month from: Divvy’s public historical trip data

  2. Unzipped the files

  3. Opened the csv files one-by-one in Excel for exploration

  4. Assessed the number of variables and the length of the data and decided to continue the data processing in RStudio

Data Description

The raw data set contains data on 5,803,720 bike rides along 13 variables:

  • ride_id <chr> : a 16-digit unique trip identifier, consisting of letters and numbers
  • rideable_type <chr> : type of bike, assuming one of three categories:
    • classic_bike
    • docked_bike
    • electric_bike
  • started_at <dttm> : the start date and time of the trip
  • ended_at <dttm> : the end date and time of the trip
  • start_station_name <chr> : the name of the station from which the bike trip started
  • start_station_id <chr> : the ID of the station from which the bike trip started
  • end_station_name <chr> : the name of the station where the bike trip ended
  • end_station_id <chr> : the ID of the station where the bike trip ended
  • start_lat <dbl> : start latitude, ranges between 41.64 and 42.07 degrees
  • start_lng <dbl> : start longitude, ranges between -87.84 and -87.52 degrees
  • end_lat <dbl> : end latitude, ranges between 0.00 and 42.37 degrees
  • end_lng <dbl> : end longitude, ranges between -88.14 and 0.00 degrees
  • member_casual <chr> : type of user, assuming one of two categories:
    • member
    • casual

Observations

  • Blank cells and missing data to check:
    • start_station_name (n_empty=839082)
    • start_station_id (n_empty=839214)
    • end_station_name (n_empty=896319)
    • end_station_id (n_empty=896460)
    • end_lat (n_missing=5855)
    • end_lng (n_missing=5855)
  • Inconsistent number of decimals to check:
    • start_lat
    • start_lng
    • end_lat
    • eng_lng
  • Outlying data to check: end_lat=0.00, end_lng=0.00
  • Data type - string to factor:
    • rideable_type
    • member_casual
    • start_station_name
    • end_station_name

    • “DIVVY CASSETTE REPAIR MOBILE STATION - DIVVY CASSETTE REPAIR MOBILE STATION”

    • “NewHastings - 2059 Hastings Warehouse Station”

  • We can spot a few typos:

    • Public Rack - Pulaski Rd &amp; 65th St–> Public Rack - Pulaski Rd & 65th St

    • Public Rack - Kedzie Ave &amp; 62nd Pl –> Public Rack - Kedzie Ave & 62nd Pl

  • We can also find inconsistent naming:

    • “Bissell St & Armitage Ave - Charging” or “Bissell St & Armitage Ave*”

    • “Base - 2132 W Hubbard” or “Base - 2132 W Hubbard Warehouse”

    • “WestChi” or “WEST CHI-WATSON”

  • and station names that don’t exist in the Divvy database:

    • “Elizabeth St & Randolph St”

    • “Stony Island Ave & 63rd St”

New variable: travel_time

bike_rides_raw <- bike_rides_raw |>

New variable: time_of_day

Classifying the extracted time by time of the day:

## a column time_of_day is created using logic with case_when()
## to classify rows into
## morning rush/morning/lunchtime/afternoon/afternoon rush/evening/night
## based on their hour of departure

bike_rides_raw <- bike_rides_raw |>
  mutate(
    time_of_day = case_when(
      hour >= 3 & hour < 6 ~ "Dawn",
      hour >= 6 & hour < 9 ~ "Early morning",
      hour >= 9 & hour < 12 ~ "Late morning",
      hour >= 12 & hour < 15 ~ "Early afternoon",
      hour >= 15 & hour < 18 ~ "Late afternoon",
      hour >= 18 & hour < 21 ~ "Early evening",
      hour >= 21 & hour < 24 ~ "Late evening",
      hour >= 0 & hour < 3 ~ "Night"
    )
  )

bike_rides_raw$time_of_day <- as.factor(bike_rides_raw$time_of_day)

bike_rides_raw$time_of_day <- ordered(bike_rides_raw$time_of_day,
  levels = c(
    "Dawn", "Early morning",
    "Late morning", "Early afternoon",
    "Late afternoon", "Early evening",
    "Late evening", "Night"
  )
)

The longest trip took 28 days. The 11 longest trips are associated with docked bikes.

On Divvy’s website, you can find what rules apply if you keep a bike out for longer than the time included in your membership or pass:

Day Pass holders: unlimited number of 3 hour rides over a 24-hour period. If you keep a bike out for longer than 3 hours at a time, you will be charged an extra $0.17 for each additional minute.

Annual Members: the first 45 minutes of each ride are included in the membership price. If you keep a bike out for longer than 45 minutes at a time, you will be charged an extra $0.17 for each additional minute.

NOTE: If you do not return a bike within a 24-hour period, you may be charged a lost or stolen bike fee of $250 (plus tax).

This means that bicycles kept out for more than one day can be considered outliers.

Note

Degree precision of latitude and longitude coordinates:

Precision can be measured by the number of decimal places in the latitude and longitude coordinates.

To identify stations accurately, we would need coordinates with 4-5 decimal places.

Knowing this, I assume that I won’t be able to reconstruct the missing station names and ID-s.

With 1,265,519 cases concerned, the question is: should I delete all these cases?

First, I filtered out the inaccurate data and now I will check if the missing data can be linked to a specific variable.

My strategy is to delete only those cases that would distort our analysis.

Investigating the missingness

Can the missing data be linked to a specific time period?

  group_by(user_type, month) |>
  summarise(

Our graph shows that the missing data cannot be linked to a specific time period. It appears throughout the year.

Would both groups of users be affected equally if we deleted all rows with missing values?

bike_rides_missing |>
  ggplot(aes(user_type)) +
  geom_bar(alpha = .5) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_number())

Both group of users have missing values and members would be slightly more affected than casual users.

Can the missing data be linked to a specific bike type?

bike_rides_missing |>
  group_by(bike_type, month) |>
  summarise(
    number_of_rides = n(),
    .groups = "drop_last"
  ) |>
  ggplot(aes(month, number_of_rides, fill = bike_type)) +
  geom_col(alpha = .5) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))

There seems to be a clear link between missing data and electric bikes.

After weighing the benefits and risks of deleting all cases with missing values, I decided not to remove these cases from our data table. It is not possible to identify the name of the start or end station of these trips, due to the imprecision of the coordinates, but deleting the more than 1 million observations concerned would bias the subsequent results of the analysis, as the deletion would adversely affect cyclist members and users who choose electric bicycles.

  outliers,
  warehouse_trips,
  no_end_coord,
  bike_rides_missing,
  start_stations,
  end_stations
)

Data Analysis

The analysis covers 5,661,506 bike rides between 1 April 2022 and 31 March 2023.

Limitations of the data

Note

The data has some limitations due to protection of user privacy:

  • We lack demographic data.

  • This means we can’t tell if a user is a local resident or a visitor.

  • Likewise, we can’t link different bike rides to the same user.

  • We don’t know how many unique users are in the database.

  • We can’t tell how many bike trips can be linked to the same user.

  • We can’t tell if a casual user has bought a single ride pass or a day pass.

  • Due to the imprecision of the coordinates, we have 1 265 519 cases with incomplete station identification.

Travel time

find_mode <- function(x) {
  u <- unique(x)
  tab <- tabulate(match(x, u))
  u[tab == max(tab)]
}

[1] 16.212
median(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # midpoint number in the ascending array of travel times
[1] 10.27
find_mode(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # the value that occurs most often

Key insights

  • Members make more trips than casual users but spend less time on their bikes, while casual users do the opposite, making fewer trips but spending more time on their bikes.

  • Members spend an average of 12.47 minutes on their bikes, while casual users cycle for an average of 21.75 minutes. The difference in average ride time between the two groups is almost 10 minutes.

  • Members use the service more on weekdays, with peak usage on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, and a decrease from Friday onward. In contrast, casual users tend to make more trips from Thursday onward and peak on the weekend.

  • The average travel time for members is fairly consistent, with no major fluctuations throughout the week, while casuals have a greater increase in their average times at weekends and on Mondays.

  • Members are more active regardless of the time of day, while the number of casual rides increases steadily from morning to late afternoon. The peak hour of the day is around 17:00 for both groups, but members also have a morning peak around 8:00. Morning cycling is less popular among casuals.

  • The most popular departure points for casuals are concentrated around tourist attractions closer to the coast, while the most popular stations for members are more spread out across the city. The University of Chicago area is an extremely popular departure point for members.

# Background

## Industry

According to the [Meddin bike-sharing map](https://bikesharingworldmap.com/), bike-sharing systems are present in 1,590 cities, in 92 countries and on every continent (except Antarctica). In April 2023, the world had 1,914 systems in operation with a fleet of 8,980,314 bikes. For the latest industry trends, read [The Meddin Bike-sharing World Map Report](https://bikesharingworldmap.com/reports/bswm_mid2022report.pdf). The origins of bike-sharing can be traced back to grassroots efforts in the Netherlands in the mid-1960s. For more historical context, see [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2022-02-26/the-dutch-anarchists-who-launched-a-bikesharing-revolution).

## Company

Cyclistic is a (fictional) bike-share company launched in 2016. It operates a fleet of **5,824 bikes** that are geotracked and locked into a network of **1419 stations** across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system at any time.

# Business Task

Until now, Cyclistic's marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped achieve this was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships.

Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as **casual riders** and customers who buy annual memberships are called **Cyclistic members**. In order to maximize revenue for the bike-sharing company, management set a clear objective to develop marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members.

## The focus of the analysis

Analysing historical bike trip data to identify trends that can guide Cyclistic's future marketing program.

## Business Questions

**In what ways do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?**

-   What **time** of the day/week/month/year do members and casual riders use the service?

-   Do members and casual users differ in **the time they spend cycling**?

-   What **types of bikes** do members and casual users prefer?

-   Are there any other differences that can help us **better understand the needs** of occasional and year-round users?

# Preparing the data

## Data Sources

The dataset is acquired from [Divvy's public data](https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html) and made available by Motivate International Inc. under this [license](https://ride.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement). It includes bike rides between **1 April 2022** and **31 March 2023**.

## Data Credibility

-   **Reliable:** Lyft Bikes and Scooters, LLC (Bikeshare) operates the City of Chicago's Divvy bicycle sharing service. Bikeshare makes certain Divvy system data owned by the City available to the public. The City of Chicago owns all right, title, and interest in the Data.

-   **Original:** the data is collected by the Divvy systems

-   **Comprehensive:** the data contains all critical information needed to answer the business question

-   **Current:** the data covers the last 12 month

-   **Cited:** the data is collected and maintained by a credible organization

-   **Complies with Data Privacy:** the data is anonymised and does not contain any personally identifiable information

-   **Unbiased:** contains data that is representative of all users of the bike share service

## Downloading and storing the data

2.  Unzipped the files

## Data Description

The raw data set contains data on **5,803,720 bike rides** along **13 variables**:

-   `ride_id` *\<chr\>* : a 16-digit unique trip identifier, consisting of letters and numbers
-   `rideable_type` ***\<chr\>*** : type of bike, assuming one of three categories:
    -   classic_bike
    -   docked_bike
    -   electric_bike
-   `started_at` *\<dttm\>* : the start date and time of the trip
-   `ended_at` *\<dttm\>* : the end date and time of the trip
-   `start_station_name` ***\<chr\>*** : the name of the station from which the bike trip started
-   `start_station_id` *\<chr\>* : the ID of the station from which the bike trip started
-   `end_station_name` ***\<chr\>*** : the name of the station where the bike trip ended
-   `end_station_id` *\<chr\>* : the ID of the station where the bike trip ended
-   `start_lat` *\<dbl\>* : start latitude, ranges between 41.64 and 42.07 degrees
-   `start_lng` *\<dbl\>* : start longitude, ranges between -87.84 and -87.52 degrees
-   `end_lat` *\<dbl\>* : end latitude, ranges between **0.00** and 42.37 degrees
-   `end_lng` *\<dbl\>* : end longitude, ranges between -88.14 and **0.00** degrees
-   `member_casual` **\<chr\>** : type of user, assuming one of two categories:
    -   member
    -   casual

## Observations

### New variable: `time_of_day`

Classifying the extracted time by time of the day:

```{r}
#| label: time-of-day-raw-04

## a column time_of_day is created using logic with case_when()
## to classify rows into
## morning rush/morning/lunchtime/afternoon/afternoon rush/evening/night
## based on their hour of departure

bike_rides_raw <- bike_rides_raw |>
  mutate(
    time_of_day = case_when(
      hour >= 3 & hour < 6 ~ "Dawn",
      hour >= 6 & hour < 9 ~ "Early morning",
      hour >= 9 & hour < 12 ~ "Late morning",
      hour >= 12 & hour < 15 ~ "Early afternoon",
      hour >= 15 & hour < 18 ~ "Late afternoon",
      hour >= 18 & hour < 21 ~ "Early evening",
      hour >= 21 & hour < 24 ~ "Late evening",
      hour >= 0 & hour < 3 ~ "Night"
    )
  )

bike_rides_raw$time_of_day <- as.factor(bike_rides_raw$time_of_day)

bike_rides_raw$time_of_day <- ordered(bike_rides_raw$time_of_day,
  levels = c(
    "Dawn", "Early morning",
    "Late morning", "Early afternoon",
    "Late afternoon", "Early evening",
    "Late evening", "Night"
  )
)

```

The minimum and maximum values show that there are unrealistic values at both extremes.

### Failed trips

Let's start with the left side of the boxplot. Bike trips of less than two minutes seem highly unrealistic. I suspect that these short trips are the result of failed docking attempts.

Filtering for negative travel times and extremely short trips:

```{r}
#| label: failed-trips-raw-05

failed_trips <- filter(bike_rides_raw, travel_time <= 1) 

nrow(failed_trips)

```

The fact that most rides end at the same coordinate from which they started proves my assumption.

Dropping failed trips:

```{r}
#| label: drop-failed-trips

bike_rides_raw <- filter(bike_rides_raw, travel_time > 1)

```

### Extremely long trips

The 28-day bike rental also seems quite extreme.

Filtering for extremely long trips:

```{r}
#| label: filter-long-trips

outliers <- filter(bike_rides_raw, travel_time > 1440)

setDT(outliers)

nrow(outliers)

```

The longest trip took 28 days. The 11 longest trips are associated with docked bikes.

On Divvy's website, you can find what rules apply if you keep a bike out for longer than the time included in your membership or pass:

> *Day Pass holders: unlimited number of 3 hour rides over a 24-hour period. If you keep a bike out for longer than 3 hours at a time, you will be charged an extra \$0.17 for each additional minute.*
>
> *Annual Members: the first 45 minutes of each ride are included in the membership price. If you keep a bike out for longer than 45 minutes at a time, you will be charged an extra \$0.17 for each additional minute.*
>
> *NOTE: If you do not return a bike within a 24-hour period, you may be charged a lost or stolen bike fee of \$250 (plus tax).*

This means that bicycles kept out for more than one day can be considered outliers.

Dropping outliers:

```{r}
#| label: drop-outliers

bike_rides_raw <- filter(bike_rides_raw, travel_time <= 1440)

```

### Coordinates

Let's take a closer look at the coordinates belonging to the missing values.

```{r}
#| label: check-coordinates

bike_rides_missing |>
  select(
    start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id,
    start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng
  ) |>
  head(10)
```

**Observations**

-   Where station names are missing, the coordinates have fewer decimals (1-2 digits).

-   If you search for these coordinates in the Divvy map, no results are returned.

![](divvy_search_na.png)

Let's try to find these coordinates in our stations data:

```{r}
#| label: filter-lat-lng 

filter(stations, lat == 41.97 & lng == -87.71)
```

We can find four different stations with four different ID-s at lat = 41.97, lng = -87.71.

::: {.callout-note collapse="false"}
Degree precision of latitude and longitude coordinates:

Precision can be measured by the number of decimal places in the latitude and longitude coordinates.

To identify stations accurately, we would need coordinates with 4-5 decimal places.
:::

![](degree_precision_vs_length.png)

Knowing this, I assume that I won't be able to reconstruct the missing station names and ID-s.

With 1,265,519 cases concerned, the question is: should I delete all these cases?

First, I filtered out the inaccurate data and now I will check if the missing data can be linked to a specific variable.

My strategy is to delete only those cases that would distort our analysis.

### Investigating the missingness

Can the missing data be linked to a specific time period?

```{r}
#| label: fig-miss-month
#| fig-cap: "Number of cases with missing data, broken down by month and user type"

bike_rides_missing |>
  group_by(user_type, month) |>
  summarise(
    number_of_rides = n(),
    .groups = "drop_last"
  ) |>
  ggplot(aes(month, number_of_rides, fill = user_type)) +
  geom_col(alpha = .5) +
  theme(
    legend.position = "right",
    legend.direction = "vertical"
  ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))
```

Our graph shows that the missing data cannot be linked to a specific time period. It appears throughout the year.

Would both groups of users be affected equally if we deleted all rows with missing values?

```{r}
#| label: fig-miss-user-type
#| dependson: "filter-na"
#| fig-cap: "Number of cases with missing data broken down by user type"

bike_rides_missing |>
  ggplot(aes(user_type)) +
  geom_bar(alpha = .5) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_number())
```

Both group of users have missing values and members would be slightly more affected than casual users.

Can the missing data be linked to a specific bike type?

```{r}
#| label: fig-miss-bike-month
#| dependson: "filter-na"
#| fig-cap: "Number of cases with missing values, broken down by bike type"

bike_rides_missing |>
  group_by(bike_type, month) |>
  summarise(
    number_of_rides = n(),
    .groups = "drop_last"
  ) |>
  ggplot(aes(month, number_of_rides, fill = bike_type)) +
  geom_col(alpha = .5) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1))
```

There seems to be a clear link between missing data and electric bikes.

After weighing the benefits and risks of deleting all cases with missing values, I decided not to remove these cases from our data table. It is not possible to identify the name of the start or end station of these trips, due to the imprecision of the coordinates, but deleting the more than 1 million observations concerned would bias the subsequent results of the analysis, as the deletion would adversely affect cyclist members and users who choose electric bicycles.

# Data Analysis

The analysis covers **5,661,506 bike rides** between **1 April 2022** and **31 March 2023**.

## Limitations of the data

::: callout-note
The data has some limitations due to protection of user privacy:

-   We lack demographic data.

-   This means we can't tell if a user is a local resident or a visitor.

-   Likewise, we can't link different bike rides to the same user.

-   We don't know how many unique users are in the database.

-   We can't tell how many bike trips can be linked to the same user.

-   We can't tell if a casual user has bought a single ride pass or a day pass.

-   Due to the imprecision of the coordinates, we have 1 265 519 cases with incomplete station identification.
:::

### Travel time

```{r}
#| label: find-mode-function 

find_mode <- function(x) {
  u <- unique(x)
  tab <- tabulate(match(x, u))
  u[tab == max(tab)]
}

```

```{r}
#| label: descriptive-time

min(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # shortest ride
max(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # longest ride
mean(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # straight average (total travel time / rides)
median(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # midpoint number in the ascending array of travel times
find_mode(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # the value that occurs most often
sd(bike_rides_clean$travel_time) # standard deviation (how dispersed the data is in relation to the mean)
```

-   Shortest ride: 1.02 min.

-   Longest ride: 1439.37 min.

-   Average ride: 16.212 min.

-   Median: 10.27 min.

```{r}
    average_travel_time = mean(travel_time),
    .groups = "drop_last"
  ) |>
  ggplot(aes(weekday, average_travel_time, fill = user_type)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge", alpha = .5) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("#BA2649", "#CEC2AE"),
    labels = c("Casual", "Member"),
    name = "User"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    labels = label_number(),
  ) +
  theme_fivethirtyeight() +
  theme(
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    legend.position = "right",
    legend.direction = "vertical",
    axis.title = element_text(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank()
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Average travel time by day of the week",
    subtitle = "Based on data from 1 April 2022 to 31 March 2023"
  ) +
  ylab("Average travel time in minutes")

```

We already saw that members make more trips than casual users but they spend less time on their bikes, while casuals do the opposite, they start less rides, but spend more time cycling.

We can also spot that the average travel time for members is fairly consistent, with no major fluctuations throughout the week, while casuals have a bigger rise in their average times at weekends and on Mondays.

This graph shows how cycling activity change throughout the day. Late afternoon (15:00-18:00) is when most people from both groups get on their bikes.\
One might think that the majority of members would cycle to work in the morning and then cycle home in the afternoon, but our data suggest that morning cycling is far less popular than afternoon cycling.

Unlike members, casual users prefer to skip the early morning rush (6:00-9:00) and cycle in the afternoon and evening hours instead.

## Key insights

-   Members make more trips than casual users but spend less time on their bikes, while casual users do the opposite, making fewer trips but spending more time on their bikes.

-   Members spend an average of 12.47 minutes on their bikes, while casual users cycle for an average of 21.75 minutes. The difference in average ride time between the two groups is almost 10 minutes.

-   Members use the service more on weekdays, with peak usage on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, and a decrease from Friday onward. In contrast, casual users tend to make more trips from Thursday onward and peak on the weekend.

-   The average travel time for members is fairly consistent, with no major fluctuations throughout the week, while casuals have a greater increase in their average times at weekends and on Mondays.

-   Members are more active regardless of the time of day, while the number of casual rides increases steadily from morning to late afternoon. The peak hour of the day is around 17:00 for both groups, but members also have a morning peak around 8:00. Morning cycling is less popular among casuals.

-   The most popular departure points for casuals are concentrated around tourist attractions closer to the coast, while the most popular stations for members are more spread out across the city. The University of Chicago area is an extremely popular departure point for members.
